                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.62/40.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">O’Shaughnessy</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-09T12:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 9, 1914, 12 noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>720. The German Minister has just called and stated that he has received a
                    telegram from his Consul in the city of Tepic stating that all foreigners
                    anticipate serious trouble and possible capture of that city by so-called
                    revolutionists. The Minister inquires if it is not possible for our Government
                    to take some measures looking to the protection of the foreign colony in that
                    city. His only vessel on the west coast is now at Guaymas where trouble is also
                    anticipated. There are about thirty Americans in Tepic and it is thought that
                    the presence of a war vessel at San Bias would afford adequate protection to the
                    foreigners in that section.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson O’Shaughnessy</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
